Q. Who was an American - A. William Bains, meaning himself; that he was about thirty years of age. Mr. Churchill then asked him what became of
Richard Cooling
that was in the ship; he said he left him at St. Helena hospital when he came away;

Q. Do you know whether Field was at home at that time - A. I looked through the window, I saw a man looking at them, I could not particularly distinguish Field so as to know him again. It was at No. 10 Shorts-Gardens, where the constable took Field. When they came out they said that Mr. Field gave them five-pence a pound for them, it came to 2 s. 11 d. they gave me a shilling, I then went home. On the next morning Mr. Low came to me about eight o'clock, I was in bed, in Belton-street he said that I had stole some brass plates from the shop, I told him first I had not, and then when he said he would not hurt any of us, I told him that I had, and who was concerned with me, and after that I went with the officer to find out the other lads. I shewed him them;
Thomas Yates
I pointed out before dinner, and Mann was going to a free and easy club that night.
